revision.text:
{{unreferenced|date=April 2018}} In document [[ISO 10303]]-226, a '''fault''' is defined as an abnormal condition or defect at the component, equipment, or sub-system level which may lead to a [[failure]].
In [[telecommunications]], according to the [[Federal Standard 1037C]] of the United States, the term ''fault'' has the following meanings: #An accidental condition that causes a [[functional unit]] to fail to perform its required function. See {{section link||Random fault}}. #A defect that causes a reproducible or catastrophic malfunction. A malfunction is considered reproducible if it occurs consistently under the same circumstances. See {{section link||Systematic fault}}. # In [[Electric power|power]] systems, an unintentional [[short-circuit]], or partial short-circuit, between energized [[conductor (material)|conductor]]s or between an energized conductor and [[ground (electricity)|ground]]. A distinction can be made between [[Symmetric fault|symmetric]] and [[asymmetric fault]]s. See [[Fault (power engineering)]].
== Random fault == A '''random fault''' is a fault that occurs as a result of [[wear]] or other [[Wear|deterioration]]. Whereas the time of a particular occurrence of such a fault cannot be determined, the rate at which such faults occur within the equipment population on average can be predicted with accuracy. Manufacturers will often accept random faults as a risk if the chances are virtually negligible. A fault can happen in virtually any object or appliance, most common with electronics and machinery. For example, an [[Xbox 360]] console will deteriorate over time due to dust buildup in the [[Computer fan|fans]]. This will cause the Xbox to overheat, cause an [http://support.xbox.com/en-GB/xbox-360/flashing-lights/two-flashinglights error], and shut the console down.{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}
== Systematic fault == '''Systematic faults''' are often a result of an [[error]] in the [[specification]] of the equipment and therefore affect all examples of that type. Such faults can remain undetected for years, until conditions conduce to create the [[failure]]. Given the same circumstances, each and every example of the equipment would fail identically at that time.
Failures in hardware can be caused by random faults or systematic faults, but failures in [[software]] are always systematic.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}
